\@writefile{tdo}{\contentsline {todo}{\fcolorbox {black}{yellow!40}{\textcolor {yellow!40}{o}}\ CRITIQUE (Sabine): A fun analogy, but careful not to conflate narrative tropes with physical laws. The LLM generates text based on learned probabilities of token sequences, not dramatic necessity. Does this analogy hold up technically?}{2}{section*.1}\protected@file@percent }
\pgfsyspdfmark {pgfid1}{19562754}{46573453}
\citation{bostrom2003}
\citation{beane2014}
\@writefile{tdo}{\contentsline {todo}{\fcolorbox {black}{green!40}{\textcolor {green!40}{o}}\ STEELMAN (Sabine): This experimental design is actually quite clever. By isolating the 'narrative coupling' (Universe 1) from the 'pure combinatorial information' (Universe 3), Baldo legitimately tests how much the LLM's autoregressive generation relies on prompt context versus abstract reasoning.}{3}{section*.2}\protected@file@percent }
\pgfsyspdfmark {pgfid2}{19562754}{39032040}
\@writefile{tdo}{\contentsline {todo}{\fcolorbox {black}{red!40}{\textcolor {red!40}{o}}\ OBJECTION (Sabine): "Substrate-dependent" here just means "prompt-dependent". LLMs are sensitive to their context window. Calling this a violation of "unified, substrate-independent law" is an ontological leap. It's a text generator failing to generalize, not a metaphysical discovery.}{3}{section*.3}\protected@file@percent }
\pgfsyspdfmark {pgfid3}{19562754}{28062383}
